d English <i>hēan</i>, the weak dative form (originally used after a preposition and article) of <i>hēah</i> ‘high’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Hendley was born in 1485, in Cranbrook, Kent, England, United Kingdom. She married Richard Bigge in 1520, in Cranbrook, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1550, in Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1485–1550":"1485–1550","1479–1533":"1479–1533","1530–1563":"1530–1563","1479":"1479","1533":"1533","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","1485":"1485","1550":"1550","4 November 1533":"4. november 1533","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"1485–1550":"1485–1550","1479–1533":"1479–1533","1530–1563":"1530–1563","1479":"1479","1533":"1533","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","1485":"1485","1550":"1550","4 November 1533":"4. marraskuuta 1533","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fr":{"1485–1550":"1485–1550","1479–1533":"1479–1533","1530–1563":"1530–1563","1479":"1479","1533":"1533","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","1485":"1485","1550":"1550","4 November 1533":"4 novembre 1533","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Joan Hendley est née en 1485, à Cranbrook, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Richard Bigge en 1520, à Cranbrook, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée en 1550, à Benenden, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 65 ans."},"de":{"1485–1550":"1485–1550","1479–1533":"1479–1533","1530–1563":"1530–1563","1479":"1479","1533":"1533","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","1485":"1485","1550":"1550","4 November 1533":"4. November 1533","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, Eng